04566nam a22007335i 9789633864449DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2022003828  a9789633864449  a(DE-B1597)633356  a(OCoLC)1338018598  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aHV1160.5.Z8bK8613 2022 4aHV1160.5.Z8bK8613 2022 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a362.73/209439223/eng/202203021 aKunt, Gergely, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Children’s Republic of Gaudiopolis :bThe History and Memory of a Children’s Home for Holocaust and War Orphans (1945–1950) /cGergely Kunt. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe History of Child Rescue in Budapest -- tA Christian Orphanage with Doors Open to All -- tGaudiopolis: Democracy as a Game and the Game of Democracy -- tImmortalizing Orphans and the War in a Communist Propaganda Film -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tSources and Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGaudiopolis (The City of Joy) was a pedagogical experiment that operated in a post–World War II orphanage in Budapest. This book tells the story of this children’s republic that sought to heal the wounds of wartime trauma, address prejudice and expose the children to a firsthand experience of democracy. The children were educated in freely voicing their opinions, questioning authority, and debating ideas. The account begins with the saving of hundreds of Jewish children during the Siege of Budapest by the Lutheran minister Gábor Sztehlo together with the International Red Cross. After describing the everyday life and practices of self-rule in the orphanage that emerged from this rescue operation, the book tells how the operation of the independent children’s home was stifled after the communist takeover and how Gaudiopolis was disbanded in 1950. The book then discusses how this attempt of democratization was erased from collective memory. The erasure began with the banning of a film inspired by Gaudiopolis. The Communist Party financed Somewhere in Europe in 1947 as propaganda about the construction of a new society, but the film’s director conveyed a message of democracy and tolerance instead of adhering to the tenets of socialist realism. The book breaks the subsequent silence on “The City of Joy,” which lasted until the fall of the Iron Curtain and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zHungary. 0aJewish orphanszHungaryzBudapestxHistory. 0aOrphanageszHungaryzBudapestxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aCentral Europe.  aHolocaust.  aHungary.  aart film.  ahistory of democracy.1 aLo Bello, Maya J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuleiman, Susan Rubin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633864449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633864449/original  a978-3-11-078048-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK